{"key":"processedPost-14630514","value":{"id":14630514,"first":14623042,"last":14649647,"when":1308366648,"utime":"06/18/11 06:10 AM","content":"<blockquote>Quote:<br /><b>bbox244 said:</b><br />Also, another way to calibrate your hygrometer is to use the salt water method, I just posted about this a couple days ago, but basically, salt and water has a critical evaporation potential of 75%, so take a ziplock with a bowl of salt water in it, and put in your hygrometer, after an hour, tune it to 75 and your done.<br /></blockquote><br /><br />That method is not appropriate for mushroom growing.&nbsp; Hygrometers are only accurate over a tiny portion of the scale.&nbsp; Always calibrate at the level you'll be operating at.&nbsp; That means use a damp towel and adjust for 99%.&nbsp; The salt method is accurate for humidors, which run at 70% to 75%.<br />RR","title":"Re: RH @ 80"}}